    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The 25% annual depreciation for the first year ($37,500) is a result of the half-year convention, not directly calculated from the 25% percentage.\n\nHere's the correct calculation:\n\n1. Initial depreciation (30% of $150,000 in the first year, like I mentioned) = $45,000\n2. Remaining adjusted basis = $150,000 - $45,000 = $105,000\n3. Depreciation for the next year (25% of the remaining basis) = $26,250\n\nFor the half-year convention, the concept is as follows:\n- For the first year, 100% of the depreciation occurs.\n- For the subsequent years, half of the anticipated annual depreciation occurs each year.\n- This concept accounts for the difficulty in determining when a long-life asset is fully depreciated, as its useful life varies by asset.\n\nIn the business equation, you would then see the asset's value being reduced year-over-year as follows:\n\nInitial Year: $150,000 (100% x $150,000)\nYear 2: $150,000 - $45,000 = $105,000\nYear 3: $105,000 / 2 = $52",
      "source": "target",
